05319nam a22008535i 9780231542470DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016034387  a97802315424707 a10.7312/palt179922doi  a(DE-B1597)480312  a(OCoLC)984683211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJC330b.P284 2017 4aJC330b.P358 2017eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a3202231 aPalti, Elías, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut13aAn Archaeology of the Political :bRegimes of Power from the Seventeenth Century to the Present /cElías Palti. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b6 b&w photographs and 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Political Thought / Political History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor’s Foreword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: A Conceptual History of the Political— The Archaeological Project -- t1. The Theological Genesis of the Political -- t2. The Tragic Scene -- t3. The Discourse of Emancipation and the Emergence of Democracy as a Problem -- t4. The Rebirth of the Tragic Scene and the Emergence of the Political as a Conceptual Problem -- tConclusion: The End of a Long Cycle— The Second Disenchantment of the World -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the past few decades, much political-philosophical reflection has been dedicated to the realm of "the political." Many of the key figures in contemporary political theory—Jacques Rancière, Alain Badiou, Reinhart Koselleck, Giorgio Agamben, Ernesto Laclau, and Slavoj iek, among others—have dedicated themselves to explaining power relations, but in many cases they take the concept of the political for granted, as if it were a given, an eternal essence.In An Archaeology of the Political, Elías José Palti argues that the dimension of reality known as the political is not a natural, transhistorical entity. Instead, he claims that the horizon of the political arose in the context of a series of changes that affirmed the power of absolute monarchies in seventeenth-century Europe and was successively reconfigured from this period up to the present. Palti traces this series of redefinitions accompanying alterations in regimes of power, thus describing a genealogy of the concept of the political. Perhaps most important, An Archaeology of the Political brings to theoretical discussions a sound historical perspective, illuminating the complex influences of both theology and secularization on our understanding of the political in the contemporary world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPolitical science-Philosophy-History. 0aPower (Social sciences)xPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPower (Social sciences)-Philosophy-History. 0aSovereignty. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2017z9783110548228oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/palt1799240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542470.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Pr